Let F' be the filtration on K defined by {F'}^p(K^n) = \operatorname {Dec}(F)^{p-n}(K^n) = Z_1^{p,n-p}. We trivially have isomorphisms
927hodge-theory-ii-1.3.4.1hodge-theory-ii-1.3.4.1.xmlEquation1.3.4.1hodge-theory-ii-1.3.4 E_r^{p,n-p}(\operatorname {Dec}(K)) = E_{r+1}^{p+n,-p}(K,F') \tag{1.3.4.1}
that are compatible with the d_r and with . The map u comes from and from the identity map (K,F') \to (K,F). This proves (i), and it remains to show that, for r\geqslant 2, E_r^{pq}(K,F') \xrightarrow {\sim } E_r^{pq}(K,F). We have \begin {aligned} Z_r^{pq}(K,F') &= Z_r^{pq}(K,F) \qquad \text {for }r\geqslant 1 \\Z_r^{pq}(K,F') \cap B_r^{pq}(K,F') &= Z_r^{pq}(K,F) \cap B_r^{pq}(K,F) \qquad \text {for }r\geqslant 2 \end {aligned} and we can then apply .

We have, by definition:

    474hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.1hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.1.xmlEquation1.3.1.1hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1         E_r^{pq}         = \operatorname {Im}(Z_r^{pq}\to  K^{p+q}/B_r^{pq})       \tag{1.3.1.1}       

    475hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.2hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.2.xmlEquation1.3.1.2hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1         = Z_r^{pq}/(B_r^{pq}\cap  Z_r^{pq})       \tag{1.3.1.2}       

    476hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.3hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.3.xmlEquation1.3.1.3hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1         = \operatorname {Ker}(K^{p+q}/B_r^{pq}\to  K^{p+q}/(Z_r^{pq}+B_r^{pq})).       \tag{1.3.1.3}       

    We can thus write

    477hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.4hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1.4.xmlEquation1.3.1.4hodge-theory-ii-1.3.1         \begin {aligned}           B_r^{p\bullet }\cap  Z_r^{p\bullet }           &\coloneqq  (dF^{p-r+1}+F^{p+1}) \cap  (d^{-1}F^{p+r}\cap  F^p)         \\&= (dF^{p-r+1}\cap  F^p) + (F^{p+1}\cap  d^{-1}F^{p+r})         \end {aligned}       \tag{1.3.1.4}       

    since dF^{p-r+1}\subset  d^{-1}F^{p+r} and F^{p+1}\subset  F^p.

If this condition is satisfied for arbitrary p and q, then by induction on r we have
               F^{p+r} \cap  dF^p         = dF^{p+r}       
      which, for large p+r, can be written as
               F^p \cap  dK         = dF^p.       \tag{2}

This filtration is compatible with the differentials:
           \begin {aligned}         dZ_1^{p+n,-p}         &\subset  F^{p+n+1}(K^{n+1}) \cap  \operatorname {Ker}(d)       \\&\subset  Z_\infty ^{p+n+1,-p}       \\&\subset  Z_1^{p+n+1,-p}.       \end {aligned}     

    Since

    919hodge-theory-ii-1.3.3.1hodge-theory-ii-1.3.3.1.xmlEquation1.3.3.1hodge-theory-ii-1.3.3         \begin {aligned}           Z_1^{p+1+n,-p-1}           &\subset  F^{p+1+n}(K^n)         \\&\subset  B_1^{p+n,-p}         \\&\subset  Z_1^{p+n,-p}         \end {aligned}       \tag{1.3.3.1}       

    the evident arrow from Z_1^{p+n,-p}/Z_1^{p+1+n,-p-1} to Z_1^{p+n,-p}/B_1^{p+n,-p} is a morphism

    920hodge-theory-ii-1.3.3.2hodge-theory-ii-1.3.3.2.xmlEquation1.3.3.2hodge-theory-ii-1.3.3         u\colon  E_0^{p,n-p}(\operatorname {Dec}(K)) \to  E_1^{p+n,-p}(K).       \tag{1.3.3.2}

Let F' be the filtration on K defined by {F'}^p(K^n) = \operatorname {Dec}(F)^{p-n}(K^n) = Z_1^{p,n-p}. We trivially have isomorphisms
927hodge-theory-ii-1.3.4.1hodge-theory-ii-1.3.4.1.xmlEquation1.3.4.1hodge-theory-ii-1.3.4 E_r^{p,n-p}(\operatorname {Dec}(K)) = E_{r+1}^{p+n,-p}(K,F') \tag{1.3.4.1}
that are compatible with the d_r and with . The map u comes from and from the identity map (K,F') \to (K,F). This proves (i), and it remains to show that, for r\geqslant 2, E_r^{pq}(K,F') \xrightarrow {\sim } E_r^{pq}(K,F). We have \begin {aligned} Z_r^{pq}(K,F') &= Z_r^{pq}(K,F) \qquad \text {for }r\geqslant 1 \\Z_r^{pq}(K,F') \cap B_r^{pq}(K,F') &= Z_r^{pq}(K,F) \cap B_r^{pq}(K,F) \qquad \text {for }r\geqslant 2 \end {aligned} and we can then apply .

Each differential d of each of the complexes U^p fits into a commutative diagram of filtered objects of the following type, where, for simplicity, we have omitted the total or complementary degree:



    \usepackage {amsmath}
    \usepackage {amssymb}
    \usepackage {tikz-cd}
  \begin {tikzcd}
        B^p/Z^{p+1}
          \ar [rrr,"d"]
          \ar [dr]
        &&& B^{p+1}/Z^{p+1}
          \ar [dd]
      \\& \operatorname {Coim}(d)
          \ar [r,"(5)"]
        & \operatorname {Im}(d)
          \ar [ur] \ar [dr]
      \\W^{p+1}/Z^{p+1}
          \ar [uu]
          \ar [ur]
          \ar [rrr,near start,swap,"(3)"]
          \ar [white,urr,near end,swap,"\color {black}(4)"]
        &&& B^{p+1}/W^{p+2}
          \ar [d]
      \\W^{p+1}/W^{p+2}
          \ar [u]
          \ar [rrr,near start,swap,"(1)"]
          \ar [white,urrr,"\color {black}(2)"description]
        &&& W^{p+1}/W^{p+2}
      \end {tikzcd}


      By hypothesis, the morphism (1) is strict.
      Since the square (2) is exactly the canonical decomposition of (1), the arrow (3) is a filtered isomorphism.
      The arrows of the trapezium (4) are isomorphisms;
      they are thus filtered isomorphisms, since (3) is a filtered isomorphism.
      The fact that (5) is a filtered isomorphism implies that d is strict.
      This proves the lemma.

